#: ../../../reference/c-api/generalized-ufuncs.rst:186
msgid "C-API for implementing elementary functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/generalized-ufuncs.rst:188
msgid ""
"The current interface remains unchanged, and ``PyUFunc_FromFuncAndData`` can "
"still be used to implement (specialized) ufuncs, consisting of scalar "
"elementary functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/generalized-ufuncs.rst:192
msgid ""
"One can use ``PyUFunc_FromFuncAndDataAndSignature`` to declare a more "
"general ufunc.  The argument list is the same as "
"``PyUFunc_FromFuncAndData``, with an additional argument specifying the "
"signature as C string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/generalized-ufuncs.rst:197
msgid ""
"Furthermore, the callback function is of the same type as before, ``void "
"(*foo)(char **args, intp *dimensions, intp *steps, void *func)``. When "
"invoked, ``args`` is a list of length ``nargs`` containing the data of all "
"input/output arguments.  For a scalar elementary function, ``steps`` is also "
"of length ``nargs``, denoting the strides used for the arguments. "
"``dimensions`` is a pointer to a single integer defining the size of the "
"axis to be looped over."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/generalized-ufuncs.rst:205
msgid ""
"For a non-trivial signature, ``dimensions`` will also contain the sizes of "
"the core dimensions as well, starting at the second entry.  Only one size is "
"provided for each unique dimension name and the sizes are given according to "
"the first occurrence of a dimension name in the signature."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/generalized-ufuncs.rst:211
msgid ""
"The first ``nargs`` elements of ``steps`` remain the same as for scalar "
"ufuncs.  The following elements contain the strides of all core dimensions "
"for all arguments in order."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/generalized-ufuncs.rst:215
msgid ""
"For example, consider a ufunc with signature ``(i,j),(i)->()``.  In this "
"case, ``args`` will contain three pointers to the data of the input/output "
"arrays ``a``, ``b``, ``c``.  Furthermore, ``dimensions`` will be ``[N, I, "
"J]`` to define the size of ``N`` of the loop and the sizes ``I`` and ``J`` "
"for the core dimensions ``i`` and ``j``.  Finally, ``steps`` will be ``[a_N, "
"b_N, c_N, a_i, a_j, b_i]``, containing all necessary strides."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/generalized-ufuncs.rst:223
msgid "Customizing core dimension size processing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/generalized-ufuncs.rst:225
msgid ""
"The optional function of type ``PyUFunc_ProcessCoreDimsFunc``, stored on the "
"``process_core_dims_func`` attribute of the ufunc, provides the author of "
"the ufunc a \"hook\" into the processing of the core dimensions of the "
"arrays that were passed to the ufunc.  The two primary uses of this \"hook\" "
"are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/generalized-ufuncs.rst:231
msgid ""
"Check that constraints on the core dimensions required by the ufunc are "
"satisfied (and set an exception if they are not)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/generalized-ufuncs.rst:233
msgid ""
"Compute output shapes for any output core dimensions that were not "
"determined by the input arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/generalized-ufuncs.rst:236
msgid ""
"As an example of the first use, consider the generalized ufunc ``minmax`` "
"with signature ``(n)->(2)`` that simultaneously computes the minimum and "
"maximum of a sequence.  It should require that ``n > 0``, because the "
"minimum and maximum of a sequence with length 0 is not meaningful. In this "
"case, the ufunc author might define the function like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/generalized-ufuncs.rst:242
msgid ""
"int minmax_process_core_dims(PyUFuncObject *ufunc,\n"
"                             npy_intp *core_dim_sizes)\n"
"{\n"
"    npy_intp n = core_dim_sizes[0];\n"
"    if (n == 0) {\n"
"        PyErr_SetString(PyExc_ValueError,\n"
"                        \"minmax requires the core dimension to \"\n"
"                        \"be at least 1.\");\n"
"        return -1;\n"
"    }\n"
"    return 0;\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/generalized-ufuncs.rst:257
msgid ""
"In this case, the length of the array ``core_dim_sizes`` will be 2. The "
"second value in the array will always be 2, so there is no need for the "
"function to inspect it.  The core dimension ``n`` is stored in the first "
"element.  The function sets an exception and returns -1 if it finds that "
"``n`` is 0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/generalized-ufuncs.rst:263
msgid ""
"The second use for the \"hook\" is to compute the size of output arrays when "
"the output arrays are not provided by the caller and one or more core "
"dimension of the output is not also an input core dimension. If the ufunc "
"does not have a function defined on the ``process_core_dims_func`` "
"attribute, an unspecified output core dimension size will result in an "
"exception being raised.  With the \"hook\" provided by "
"``process_core_dims_func``, the author of the ufunc can set the output size "
"to whatever is appropriate for the ufunc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/generalized-ufuncs.rst:272
msgid ""
"In the array passed to the \"hook\" function, core dimensions that were not "
"determined by the input are indicated by having the value -1 in the "
"``core_dim_sizes`` array.  The function can replace the -1 with whatever "
"value is appropriate for the ufunc, based on the core dimensions that "
"occurred in the input arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/generalized-ufuncs.rst:279
msgid ""
"The function must never change a value in ``core_dim_sizes`` that is not -1 "
"on input.  Changing a value that was not -1 will generally result in "
"incorrect output from the ufunc, and could result in the Python interpreter "
"crashing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/generalized-ufuncs.rst:284
msgid ""
"For example, consider the generalized ufunc ``conv1d`` for which the "
"elementary function computes the \"full\" convolution of two one-dimensional "
"arrays ``x`` and ``y`` with lengths ``m`` and ``n``, respectively.  The "
"output of this convolution has length ``m + n - 1``. To implement this as a "
"generalized ufunc, the signature is set to ``(m),(n)->(p)``, and in the "
"\"hook\" function, if the core dimension ``p`` is found to be -1, it is "
"replaced with ``m + n - 1``.  If ``p`` is *not* -1, it must be verified that "
"the given value equals ``m + n - 1``. If it does not, the function must set "
"an exception and return -1. For a meaningful result, the operation also "
"requires that ``m + n`` is at least 1, i.e. both inputs can't have length 0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/generalized-ufuncs.rst:296
msgid "Here's how that might look in code:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/generalized-ufuncs.rst:298
msgid ""
"int conv1d_process_core_dims(PyUFuncObject *ufunc,\n"
"                             npy_intp *core_dim_sizes)\n"
"{\n"
"    // core_dim_sizes will hold the core dimensions [m, n, p].\n"
"    // p will be -1 if the caller did not provide the out argument.\n"
"    npy_intp m = core_dim_sizes[0];\n"
"    npy_intp n = core_dim_sizes[1];\n"
"    npy_intp p = core_dim_sizes[2];\n"
"    npy_intp required_p = m + n - 1;\n"
"\n"
"    if (m == 0 && n == 0) {\n"
"        // Disallow both inputs having length 0.\n"
"        PyErr_SetString(PyExc_ValueError,\n"
"            \"conv1d: both inputs have core dimension 0; the function \"\n"
"            \"requires that at least one input has size greater than 0.\");\n"
"        return -1;\n"
"    }\n"
"    if (p == -1) {\n"
"        // Output array was not given in the call of the ufunc.\n"
"        // Set the correct output size here.\n"
"        core_dim_sizes[2] = required_p;\n"
"        return 0;\n"
"    }\n"
"    // An output array *was* given.  Validate its core dimension.\n"
"    if (p != required_p) {\n"
"        PyErr_Format(PyExc_ValueError,\n"
"                \"conv1d: the core dimension p of the out parameter \"\n"
"                \"does not equal m + n - 1, where m and n are the \"\n"
"                \"core dimensions of the inputs x and y; got m=%zd \"\n"
"                \"and n=%zd so p must be %zd, but got p=%zd.\",\n"
"                m, n, required_p, p);\n"
"        return -1;\n"
"    }\n"
"    return 0;\n"
"}"
msgstr ""
